    "However, with expanded data gathering duties arising alongside privacy sensitivities after General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) [45] adoption, persistent transparency-accountability tradeoffs remain negotiated through non-binding codes subordinate to commercial constraints [2].So in effect, the EU trajectory that informed the DSA represents gradual acknowledgment of self-governance limitations, giving way to formal cooperation against complex threats spanning borders.",
    "However, the challenge lies in reconciling binding regulations with the evidence required for accuracy, oversight, and proportionality, amidst pressing calls for action.",
    "The binding nature of the DSA significantly broadens obligations, aiming to strike a balance in addressing these challenges.",
    "Limitations and persistent gaps in the DSAThe DSA adopted in 2022 represents a significant evolution from the self-regulatory Code to a comprehensive legal framework for regulating platforms' content moderation practices, with a comparison summarized below in Table 2.",
    "3While the Digital Services Act represents progress beyond the self-regulatory efforts previously seen, scholars warned about some of its persistent gaps, inconsistencies and unexamined assumptions [78,82,104,109,169]."
